{
    title: "Weak Credentials Discovered via Bruteforce Attack",

    summary: "During the security test, it was possible to perform a bruteforce attack against one or more services, thus guessing valid credentials.",

    description: "Bruteforce attacks are a type of password guessing attack in which multiple login attempts are made automatically, trying out either a list of commonly used passwords, a generated list of variants of such passwords, or a list of all possible character combinations for a given password length.\n\n{% include 'summary' %}",

    recommendations: "Implement strong password policies to prevent simple guessing. Additionally, implement a password rotation scheme so any given password does not stay active long enough for a slow bruteforce attack to succeed. Furthermore, implementing a CAPTCHA can also make bruteforce attacks longer to run, since the attacker cannot successfuly automate multiple login attempts within a given timeframe.\n\nWith all of these measures combined, it should be possible to make a system virtually invulnerable to generic bruteforce attacks. However, an attacker with prior knowledge of either part of a password or a password generation scheme could still try to manually guess valid credentials. It is therefore also recommended to implement an account lockout policy, to automatically lock any accounts after a certain number of failed login attempts.",

    details: "The following credentials were discovered by performing a network based bruteforce attack:\n\n| Host | Port | Service | Login | Password |\n| -- | -- | -- | -- | -- |\n{% for item in credentials %}| {{ item.host }} | {{ item.port }} | {{ item.service }} | {{ item.login }} | {{ item.password }} |\n{% endfor %}",

    references: [
